It&#x27;d be great if it were possible to use URLs like

{code}
.../commits/all?search=blabla&redirect=true
{code}

to link directly to commits by some unique text included in their description.

An integration I use generates commit descriptions before the actual commit, so the hash doesn&#x27;t yet exist. And then it needs to show a link to this commit on Bitbucket.

I am attempting to describe a textual diff algorithm. In order to do so, I need to render the following text:

{code}
<    >
{code}

inside table cells. Meaning, I need the value {{<}} followed by 4 spaces, followed by {{>}} to show up in a table cell. I have looked high and far but could not find a workaround for doing so.

Continuing from Issue BCLOUD-8020,

Null content for automated comments are still not appearing în 2.0 and for the 1.0 they are not showing up at all.

2.0 response

{code}
#!json

"content": {
    "raw": null,
    "markup": "markdown",
    "html": ""
  },

{code}

Because right now if you hit

{code}
$ curl -L https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/foo/bar/pullrequests/10585/diff?context=1
{code}

The {{context}} param gets lost in the redirect and so you get too much unified context output.

for example, https://bitbucket.org/skskeyserver/sks-keyserver/downloads contains:

{code}
#!html
            <td class="name"><a class="execute" href="
                    /skskeyserver/sks-keyserver/downloads/sks-1.1.6.tgz">sks-1.1.6.tgz</a>
            </td>
{code}

This makes systems like debian&#x27;s automated source update trackers fail (see uscan(1), debian/watch).

Please don&#x27;t add this leading whitespace in the href!
